          "body": "With verse 12 the genre shifts from poem to autobiography. The Preacher introduces himself: king over Israel in Jerusalem, and he sets his heart — his full deliberate rational capacity (*lev*) — to seek and explore by wisdom all that is done under heaven (1:13). The word for explore is *tur*, used elsewhere for the scouts who explored Canaan (Numbers 13:2) — the Preacher is doing reconnaissance on the whole territory of human experience. His credentials for the experiment are unimpeachable: he has surpassed all who preceded him in Jerusalem in wisdom (1:16), and his mind has experienced 'a wealth of wisdom and knowledge' (*daat*). The survey of all works done under the sun produces a single verdict (1:14): 'vanity and striving after wind.' The wind-metaphor adds what *hevel* alone does not fully say — it is not merely that results evaporate, but that the pursuit itself is like grasping at wind: effort directed at something uncatchable by nature."
